osophical and theological idea of “ground,” Van Horn argues that ground—when read as earth-ground, as soil—offers a symbol for conceiving of the effects of climate change as collective and yet located, as communal and yet differential. In so doing, he offers critical interventions on theorizations of hope and political action amid the crises of climate change.Drawing on soil science, theopoetics, feminist ethics, poststructuralism, process philosophy, and more, On the Ground asks: In the face of global climate catastrophe, how might one theorize this calamitous experience as shared and yet particular, as interconnected and yet contextual? Might there be a way to conceptualize our interconnected experiences without erasing critical constitutive differences, particularly of social and ecological location? How might these conceptual interven­tions catalyze pluralistic, anti-racist planetary politics amid the Anthropocene? In short, the book addresses these queries: What philosophical and theological concepts can soil create? How might soil inspire and help re-imagine forms of planetary politics in the midst of climate change? On the Ground thus roots us in a robust theoretical symbol in the hopes of producing and proliferating intersectional responses to climate change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aClimatic changesxPolitical aspects. 0aClimatic changesxSocial aspects. 0aHuman ecologyxPolitical aspects. 0aHuman ecologyxSocial aspects. 0aSoils. 4aEnvironment. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / Ethics.2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  aEcotheology.  aclimate change.  acontinental philosophy.  aenvironmental studies.  aground.  ahope.  apolitical theory.  asoil.  atheopoetics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Engli